Model Checking

Fundamental Concepts

Transition Systems

Definition 1 (Transition System) Formaly a transition system \(T\) is a tuple \((S, \texttt{Act}, \rightarrow, S_0, \texttt{AP}, L)\) where

  • \(S\) countable set of states
  • \(\texttt{Act}\) set of actions
  • \(\rightarrow \ \subseteq S \times \texttt{Act}\times S\) a transition relation
  • \(S_0 \subseteq S\) a set of initial states
  • set of atomic propositions \(\texttt{AP}\) with
  • a labeling function \(L : S \rightarrow 2^{\texttt{AP}}\) that assigns propositions to each state
Differences to finite automata
  • Possibly infinity state space.
  • No accepting states.
  • Multiple initial states.
Execution Fragment
An execution fragment of a transition system is an alternating sequence sequence of states and actions:

\[ \rho = s_0 \alpha_1 s_1 \alpha_2 \ ... \text{ such that } s_i \xrightarrow{\alpha_{i+1}} s_{i+1}\]

Maximal
An execution fragment is maximal iff. it is infinite or it is ending in a terminal state.
Initial
An execution fragment is initial iff. it starts in an initial state.
Execution
An execution is an initial & maximal execution fragment. (corresponds to run on automata)
Path
Let \(s_0 \alpha_1 s_1 ...\) be an execution, then \(s_0s_1 ...\) is a path. In other words a path is the sequence of states of an execution.
Reachable fragment
\(Reach(T)\) set of states that appear on some path.
Trace
Let \(s_0s_1...\) be a path, then \(L(s_0)L(s_1)...\) is a trace. In other words a trace is the sequence of atomic propositions that hold along a path.

Program Graphs

Program graphs are an abstraction of (imperative) programs.

Definition 2 (Program Graph) A program graph is a tuple

\[(Loc, \texttt{Act}, Effect, \hookrightarrow, Loc_0, g_0)\]

where

  • \(Loc\) is a set of locations (roughtly corresponds to code lines)
  • \(\texttt{Act}\) is a set of actions
  • \(Effect: \texttt{Act}\times Eval(Var) \rightarrow Eval(Var)\) models the effect of actions
  • \(\hookrightarrow \subseteq Loc \times Cond(Var) \times \texttt{Act}\times Loc\) is the edge relation
  • \(g_0 \in Cond(Var)\) is the initial condition

Translating Program Graphs to Transition Systems

Let \(PG = (Loc, \texttt{Act}, Effect, \hookrightarrow, Loc_0, g_0)\) be a program graph. Then this can be modeled by the transition system \((S, \texttt{Act}, \rightarrow I, \texttt{AP}, L)\) where

  • \(S = Loc \times Eval(Var)\)

  • \(\rightarrow \subseteq S \times \texttt{Act}\times S\) can be deduced by the following rule

    \[\frac{l \xhookrightarrow{g:\alpha} l' \land \eta \models g} {\langle l, \eta \rangle \xrightarrow{\alpha} \langle l', Effect(\alpha, \eta) \rangle}\]

  • \(I = \{ \langle l, \eta \rangle | l \in Loc_0, \eta \models g_0 \}\)

  • \(L( \langle l, \eta \rangle) = \{l\} \cup \{g \in Cond(Var) | \eta \models g \}\)

Interleaving

We can model multi-threaded execution without shared variables by interleaving the transition systems.

Definition 3 (Interleaving transition systems) Let \(TS_1, TS_2\) be two transition systems. Then

\[TS_1 \ ||| \ TS_2 := (S_1 \times S_2, \texttt{Act}_1 \uplus \texttt{Act}_2, \rightarrow, I_1 \times I_2, \texttt{AP}_1 \uplus \texttt{AP}_2, L)\]

  • \(L(\langle s_1, s_2 \rangle) = L_1(s_1) \cup L_2(s_2)\)
  • And \(\rightarrow\) can be deduced by the following rule: \[ \frac{s_1 \xrightarrow{\alpha} s_1'} {\langle s_1, \textcolor{gray}{s_2} \rangle \xrightarrow{\alpha} \langle s_1', \textcolor{gray}{s_2}\rangle} \text{ and } \frac{s_2 \xrightarrow{\alpha} s_2'} {\langle \textcolor{gray}{s_1}, s_2 \rangle \xrightarrow{\alpha} \langle \textcolor{gray}{s_1}, s_2'\rangle} \]

We can model multi-threaded execution with shared variables by interleaving the program graphs.

Definition 4 (Interleaving program graphs) Let \(PG_1, PG_2\) be two program graphs over the same variables. Then \(PG_1 \ ||| \ PG_2 := (Loc_1 \times Loc_2, \texttt{Act}_1 \uplus \texttt{Act}_2, Effect, \hookrightarrow,\)
\(Loc_{0,1} \uplus Loc_{0,2}, g_{0, 1} \land g_{0, 2})\)

  • \(Effect(\alpha, \eta) = Effect_i(\alpha, \eta)\) for \(\alpha \in \texttt{Act}_i\).
  • And \(\hookrightarrow\) can be deduced by the following rule: \[ \frac{l_1 \xhookrightarrow{g:\alpha} l_1'} {\langle l_1, \textcolor{gray}{l_2} \rangle \xhookrightarrow{g:\alpha} \langle l_1', \textcolor{gray}{l_2}\rangle} \text{ and } \frac{l_2 \xhookrightarrow{g:\alpha} l_2'} {\langle \textcolor{gray}{l_1}, l_2 \rangle \xhookrightarrow{g:\alpha} \langle \textcolor{gray}{l_1}, l_2'\rangle} \]
Important

In general it does not hold that \(TS(PG_1) \ ||| \ TS(PG_1) = TS(PG_1 \ ||| \ PG_2)\)

State Explosion Problem

State space grows exponentially with number of threads and variables.

Linear Time Properties

Definition 5 (Linear Time Property) A linear-time property over some atomic propositions \(\texttt{AP}\) is a subset of \(\left(2^{\texttt{AP}}\right)^\omega\).

A transitionsystem \(TS\) satisfies a LT property \(P\)

\[TS \models P \text{ iff. } Traces(TS) \subseteq P\]

Invariant
LT property of the form \(A^\omega\) for some \(A \subseteq 2^{\texttt{AP}}\) i.e. âsome property holds foreverâ
Persistance Property
LT property of the form \({(2^{\texttt{AP}})}^* A^\omega\) i.e. âsome property eventually holds foreverâ
Closure
For a LT property \(P\) the closure contains all traces \(t\) such that for each prefix of \(t\) a trace in \(P\) has the same prefix.

Definition 6 (Safety Property) A LT property \(S\) over \(\texttt{AP}\) is a safety property if for all \(\sigma \in (2^{\texttt{AP}})^\omega \setminus S\) we can find a âbad prefixâ \(\hat{\sigma}\) such that no word in \(S\) has prefix \(\hat{\sigma}\).

This is equivalent to:

\[cl(S) = S\]

Definition 7 (Liveness Property) LT property \(L\) over \(\texttt{AP}\) is a liveness property iff. it âdoes not exclude a any finite executionâ:

\[pref(L) = ({2^{\texttt{AP}}})^*\]

This is equivalent to:

\[cl(L) = 2^{\texttt{AP}}\]

Theorem 1 (LT-Properties vs Traces) Let \(TS, TS'\) be transition systems without terminal states:

\[\begin{align} Traces(TS) \quad & \subseteq \quad Traces(TS') \\ & \text{iff.} \\ TS' \models P \quad & \Rightarrow \quad TS \models P , \text{ for all LT-props } P\\ \end{align}\]

For safety property we know that:

\[\begin{align} Traces_{fin}(TS) \quad & \subseteq \quad Traces_{fin}(TS') \\ & \text{iff.} \\ TS' \models P \quad & \Rightarrow \quad TS \models P , \text{ for all \textbf{safety} props } P\\ \end{align}\]

Corollary 1

\(Traces(TS) = Traces(TS')\) iff. \(TS\) and \(TS'\) satisfy the same LT properties and analogously
\(Traces_{fin}(TS) = Traces_{fin}(TS')\) iff. \(TS\) and \(TS'\) satisfy the same safety properties.

Finite Trace Equivalence \(\neq\) Trace Equivalence

Here \(Traces_{fin}(\mathcal{T}) \subseteq Traces_{fin}(\mathcal{T'})\) but \(Traces(\mathcal{T}) \not \subseteq Traces(\mathcal{T'})\)

Lemma 1 If \(\mathcal{T}'\) is image finite (ger: endlich verzweigt) we know that:

\[Traces_{fin}(\mathcal{T}) \subseteq Traces_{fin}(\mathcal{T'}) \Leftrightarrow Traces(\mathcal{T}) \not \subseteq Traces(\mathcal{T'})\]

Theorem 2 (Decomposition Theorem) For every LT-property \(P\) we can find a safety-property \(E_{save}\) and a liveness-propery \(E_{live}\) such that

\[P = E_{save} \cap E_{live}\]

one possible decomposition is given by

\[P = \underbrace{cl(P)}_{E_{safe}} \cap \underbrace{(P \cup ((2^\texttt{AP})^\omega\setminus cl(P))}_{E_{live}}\]

\(\omega\)-regular LT-properties

Definition 8 (\(\omega\)-regular Expression) An \(\omega\)-regular expression has the form:

\[G = E_1.F_1^\omega+ ... + E_n.F_n^\omega\]

where \(E_i, F_i\) are regular expressions.

If a LT property can be defined by an \(\omega\)-regular expression we call it \(\omega\)-regular property

Definition 9 (Synchronous Product) Let:

  • \(TS := (S, \texttt{Act}, \rightharpoonup, I, \texttt{AP}, L)\) without terminal states
  • \(A := (Q, \Sigma, \rightharpoondown, Q_0, F)\) and NFA
    • \(\Sigma = 2^{\texttt{AP}}\) (A has to define traces)
    • \(Q_0 \cap F = \emptyset\) (A canât accept \(\varepsilon\) because this safetyproperty would be unsatisfiable)

Then:

\[TS \otimes A := (S', \texttt{Act}, \rightarrow, I', \texttt{AP}', L')\]

  • \(S' = S \times Q\)
  • \(\texttt{AP}' = Q\)
  • \(L'( \langle s, q \rangle) = \{q\}\)
  • \(\rightarrow\) can be deduced by:

\[\frac{s \xrightharpoonup{\alpha} \textcolor{orange}{t} \land q \xrightharpoondown{L(\textcolor{orange}{t})} p} {\langle {s}, {q} \rangle \xrightarrow{\alpha} \langle {\textcolor{orange}{t}}, {p} \rangle}\]

  • \(I' = \{ \langle s_0, q \rangle | s_0 \in I \land \exists q_0 \in Q_0 . q_0 \xrightharpoondown{L(s_0)} q \}\)

Theorem 3 Let \(TS\) be some transition system. \(E_{safe}\) a safety property and \(A\) an NFA that recognizes the bad prefixes of \(E_{safe}\). Then:

\[TS \models E_{safe} \Leftrightarrow TS \otimes A \text{ has no reachable accepting states}\]

Definition 10 (BÃ¼chi automaton) A nondeterministic BÃ¼chi automaton (NBA) is a tuple \((Q, \Sigma, \delta, Q_0, F)\) where:

  • \(Q\) is a finite set of states
  • \(\Sigma\) is a finite alphabet
  • \(\delta: Q \times \Sigma \rightarrow 2^Q\) a transition function
  • \(Q_0 \subseteq Q\) a set of initial states
  • \(F \subseteq Q\) set of accepting states

Acceptance condition: There exists a run that infinitely often visits an accepting state.

NFA vs.Â NBA
Property NFA NBA
Recognizes: regular languages \(\omega\)-regular languages
Closure \(\cup\) union operator union operator
Closure \(\cap\) product construction GNBA product
Closure \(\neg\) build DFA and complement F complex procedure
Determinism NFA = DFA DBA \(\subsetneq\) NBA

Verifying \(\omega\)-regular Safety Properties

Idea
Define BÃ¼chi automaton \(\mathfrak{A}\) for bad behaviour \(E\). The atomic property \(F\) labels all accepting states of \(\mathfrak{A}\). Check if

\[T \otimes \mathfrak{A} \models \text{ eventually forever } \neg F\]

Here \(\otimes\) is defined like in DefinitionÂ 9.

Theorem 4 (Persistence Property Check) Let \(P\) be some persistence property of the form â\(\text{eventually forever } \varphi\)â. Then it equivalent:

  1. \(\Leftrightarrow TS \models P\)
  2. \(\Leftrightarrow \exists s. (s \in \text{Reach}(TS) \land s \not \models \varphi\land s \text{ is on cycle})\)
  3. \(\Leftrightarrow \exists C. (C \text{ is reachable } \land C \text{ is a SCC} \land C \cap \{ s \in S | s \not \models \varphi\} \neq \emptyset)\)
Strongly Connected Component (SCC)
Set of states \(C\) such that for all \(x, y \in C\): \(x\) is reachable from \(y\).

SCC Method

  • compute all inclusion maximal SCCs
  • remove unreachable SCCs
  • check for a state \(s \models \neg \varphi\)
Not practical

Cycle Method

NaÃ¯ve way: \(\Theta(|V| \cdot |E|)\)

  • use DFS to find states \(s \models \neg \varphi\)
  • use second DFS to check wether cycle is reachable from itself (i.e.Â belongs to cycle)

ImprÃ¶vement: \(\Theta(|V| + |E|)\)

  • use outer DFS to find states \(s \models \neg \varphi\)
  • use inner DFS to check wether cycle is reachable from itself while avoiding states visited in a previous inner DFS, i.e.Â maintain one visited set across all executions of the inner DFS.

Linear Temporal Logic (LTL)

Definition 11 For a set of atomic propositions \(\texttt{AP}\) we give the BNF grammar for LTL:

  • \(\varphi= a \text{ for } a \in \texttt{AP}\)
  • \(\varphi= \texttt{true}| \varphi\lor \varphi| \neg \varphi\)
  • \(\varphi= \bigcirc\varphi\) ânextâ
  • \(\varphi= \varphi\textbf{U}\varphi\) âuntilâ

Additionally we will use the following derived operators:

  • the usual:
    \(\texttt{false}, \lor, \leftarrow, \rightarrow, \leftrightarrow, \otimes\)
  • modal operators:
    • âeventuallyâ \(\diamond\varphi:= \texttt{true}\textbf{U}\varphi\)
    • âalwaysâ \(\square\varphi:= \neg \diamond\neg \varphi\)
  • temporal operators:
    • âreleaseâ \(\varphi\textbf{R}\psi := \neg (\neg \varphi\textbf{U}\neg \psi)\)
    • âweak untilâ \(\varphi\textbf{W}\psi := (\varphi\textbf{U}\psi) \lor \square\varphi\)
    • âstrong releaseâ \(\varphi\textbf{M}\psi := (\varphi\textbf{R}\psi) \land \diamond\varphi\)

Equivalences

Dualities:

  • \(\neg \square\varphi\equiv \diamond\neg \varphi\)
  • \(\neg \bigcirc\varphi\equiv \bigcirc\neg \varphi\)
  • \(\neg (\varphi\textbf{U}\psi) \equiv \neg \varphi\textbf{R}\neg \psi\)
  • \(\neg (\varphi\textbf{U}\psi) \equiv (\varphi\land \neg \psi) \textbf{R}(\neg \varphi\land \neg \psi)\)
  • \(\neg (\varphi\textbf{W}\psi) \equiv \neg \varphi\textbf{M}\neg \psi\)
  • \(\neg (\varphi\textbf{W}\psi) \equiv (\varphi\land \neg \psi) \textbf{U}(\neg \varphi\land \neg \psi)\)

Absorbtion:

  • \(\square\square\varphi\equiv \square\varphi\)
  • \(\diamond\diamond\varphi\equiv \diamond\varphi\)
  • \(\square\diamond\square\varphi\equiv \diamond\square\varphi\)
  • \(\diamond\square\diamond\varphi\equiv \square\diamond\varphi\)
  • \(\varphi\textbf{U}(\varphi\textbf{U}\psi) \equiv \varphi\textbf{U}\psi\)
  • \((\varphi\textbf{U}\psi) \textbf{U}\psi \equiv \varphi\textbf{U}\psi\)

Distribution:

  • \(\bigcirc(\varphi\textbf{U}\psi) \equiv (\bigcirc\varphi\textbf{U}\bigcirc\psi)\)
  • \(\diamond(\varphi\lor \psi) \equiv \diamond\varphi\lor \diamond\psi\)
  • \(\square(\varphi\land \psi) \equiv \square\varphi\land \square\psi\)
Watch out for these false friends
  • \(\diamond(\varphi\land \psi) \not \equiv \diamond\varphi\land \diamond\psi\)
  • \(\square(\varphi\lor \psi) \not \equiv \square\varphi\lor \square\psi\)

Expansion:

  • \(\diamond\varphi\equiv \varphi\lor \bigcirc\diamond\varphi\)
  • \(\square\varphi\equiv \varphi\land \bigcirc\square\varphi\)
  • \(\varphi\textbf{U}\psi \equiv \psi \lor (\varphi\land \bigcirc(\varphi\textbf{U}\psi))\)

LTL Model Checking

Definition 12 (Generalized BÃ¼chi Automata) A Generalized Non-deterministic BÃ¼chi Automaton (GNBA) is a tuple \((Q, \Sigma, \delta, Q_0, \mathfrak{F})\) where

\[\mathfrak{F} = \{ F_1, ..., F_k \} \text{ with } F_i \subseteq Q\]

A run \(r_1r_2...\) on this automaton is accepting if:

\[\forall F_j. \exists^\infty i. r_i \in F_j\]

Definition 13 (Closure)

Let \(\varphi\) be an LTL-formula. Then the closure of \(\varphi\) contains all subformulas of \(\varphi\) and their negation1. We denote the closure of \(\varphi\) with \(cl(\varphi)\).

Definition 14 (Elementary Sets) Let \(\varphi\) be an LTL-formula. Then a set \(B \subseteq cl(\varphi)\) is elementary if it is:

  1. Maximaly Consistent for \(\land, \neg\)
    • \(\varphi\land \psi \in B \Leftrightarrow \varphi\in B \land \psi \in B\)
    • \(\varphi\notin B \Leftrightarrow \neg \varphi\in B\)
    • \(true \in cl(\varphi) \Rightarrow true \in B\)
  2. Locally Consistent for \(\textbf{U}\)
    for every \(\varphi\textbf{U}\psi \in cl(\sigma)\):
    • \(\psi \in B \Rightarrow \varphi\textbf{U}\psi \in B\)
    • \(\varphi\textbf{U}\psi \in B \land \psi \notin B \Rightarrow \varphi\in B\)

Definition 15 (LTL to GNBA) Let \(\varphi\) be an LTL-formula over \(\texttt{AP}\). We assume that \(\varphi\) only contains \(\land, \neg, \bigcirc, \textbf{U}\).

  • \(\Sigma := 2^{\texttt{AP}}\)
  • \(Q :=\) elementary sets of \(\varphi\)
  • \(Q_0 :=\) all elementary sets containing \(\varphi\)
  • \(B' \in \delta(B, l)\) iff.
    • \(l = B \cap \texttt{AP}\) i.e.Â all outgoing edges are labeled with \(B \cap \texttt{AP}\)
    • \(\bigcirc\varphi\in B \Leftrightarrow \varphi\in B'\)
    • \(\varphi\textbf{U}\psi \in B \Leftrightarrow (\psi \in B \lor (\varphi\in B \land \varphi\textbf{U}\psi \in B'))\)
  • \(\mathfrak{F} := \{ F_{\varphi_1 \textbf{U}\varphi_2} \ | \ \varphi_1 \textbf{U}\varphi_2 \in cl(\varphi)\}\) where
    \(F_{\varphi_1 \textbf{U}\varphi_2} := \{ B \in Q | \varphi_1 \textbf{U}\varphi_2 \notin B \text{ or } \varphi_2 \in B \}\)
Note

For NBA \(A\) the NBA for \(\overline{A}\) has \(c^{n^2}\) states in worst case.

Solution: First negate the formula and then construct the NBA. I.E. use \(A_{\neg \varphi} \equiv \overline{A}\).

Size of NBA can be exponential

The worst-case runtime for constructing an NBA that recognizes a formula is exponential. This is because the constructed NBA can be exponentially large. For example for \(n \in \mathbb{N}\) consider

\[\varphi_n := \bigwedge_{a \in \texttt{AP}} \bigwedge_{0 \leq i < n} (\bigcirc^i a \leftrightarrow \bigcirc^{n+i} a)\]

Intuitively we can see that after reading the first \(n\) characters the automaton has to remember for all \(0 \leq i < 0\) and every \(a \in \texttt{AP}\) if \(a\) holds at position \(i\).

Definition 16 (Algorithm for LTL Model Checking) Given an LTL-formula \(\varphi\) and a transition system \(TS\).

  1. Calculate a GNBA \(G_{\neg \varphi}\) that recognizes \(\neg \varphi\).
  2. Calculate a NBA \(A_{\neg \varphi}\) that recognizes the same language as \(G_{\neg \varphi}\).
  3. Build the synchronous product \(TS \otimes A_{\neg \varphi}\)
  4. Check if \(TS \otimes A_{\neg \varphi} \models \diamond\square\neg F\)

Time complexity: \(O( |TS| \cdot 2^{|\varphi|} )\)

Computation Tree Logic (CTL)

Definition 17 (CTL) For a set of atomic propositions \(\texttt{AP}\) we give the BNF grammar for CTL state-formulas:

  • \(\Phi = a \text{ for } a \in \texttt{AP}\)
  • \(\Phi = \texttt{true}\mid \Phi \lor \Phi \mid \neg \Phi\)
  • \(\Phi = \exists \varphi\mid \forall \varphi\)

And the following grammar for CTL path-formulas:

  • \(\varphi= \bigcirc\Phi\) ânextâ
  • \(\varphi= \Phi \textbf{U}\Phi\) âuntilâ

Additionally we will use the same derived operators as with DefinitionÂ 11:

Definition 18 (CTL Semantics) TODO

The model of a CTL formula consists of a transition system and a state.

For a fixed transition system \(TS\) with states \(S\) we define:

\[Sat(\Phi) = \{ s \in S \mid TS, s \models \Phi \}\]

Let \(S_0\) be the set of initial states of \(TS\). Then we can lift the models relation to transition systems in the following way:

\[TS \models \Phi \quad :\Leftrightarrow \quad S_0 \subseteq Sat(\Phi)\]

CTL vs LTL

Theorem 5 (From CTL to LTL) Let \(\Phi\) be a CTL-formula and \(\varphi\) the LTL-formula obtained by deleting all quantifiers from \(\Phi\). Then:

\[\Phi \equiv \varphi\textbf{ or } \Phi \text{ is not definable in LTL}\]

Theorem 6 (Comparison of CTL+)

CTL Model Checking

First bring the formula into existential normal form.

\[\begin{align} Sat(\texttt{true}) &= S \\ Sat(a) &= \{ s \in S \mid a \in L(s) \} \\ Sat(\neg \Phi) &= S \setminus Sat(\Phi) \\ Sat(\Phi \land \Psi) &= Sat(\Phi) \cap Sat(\Psi) \\ Sat(\exists \bigcirc\Phi) &= \{s \in S \mid Post(s) \cap Sat(\Phi) \neq \emptyset \}\\ Sat(\exists \square\Phi) &= \{s \in S \mid \exists \Phi \text{-lasso starting in }s\}\\ Sat(\exists (\Phi \textbf{U}\Psi)) &= \{s \in S \mid \exists \Phi \text{-path from }s \text{ to a } \Psi \text{-node} \}\\ \end{align}\]

How to find nodes with a \(\Phi\)-lassos with Fixpoints

  1. Delete all \(s\) where \(s \not \models \Phi\)
  2. Delete \(s\) if it has no (undeleted) successors.
  3. Repeat until no change. (This is the fixpoint part of the algo)

How to find nodes with a \(\Phi\)-lassos with SCCs

  1. Delete all \(s\) where \(s \not \models \Phi\)
  2. Find all (non-trivial)2 SCCs. These will form the loop part of the lasso.
  3. Find all nodes from which an SCC from Step 2 is reachable. This is the rope part of the lasso.

How to find nodes with a \(\Phi\)-path to a \(\Psi\)-node with Fixpoints

  1. Mark all \(\Psi\)-nodes
  2. Mark all predecessors of marked nodes
  3. Repeat until no change. (This is the fixpoint part of the algo)

Complexity landscape

First we define the considered problems.

LTL Model Checking Problem (LTL-QUERY)
Given \(TS\) and \(\varphi\). Does \(TS \models \varphi\)?
LTL Satisfiability Problem (LTL-[UN]SAT)
Given \(\varphi\). Does a \(TS\) exists such that \(TS \models \varphi\)? [resp. \(TS \not \models \varphi\)]
LTL Validity Problem (LTL-VALID)
Given \(\varphi\). Does it hold for all \(TS\) that \(TS \models \varphi\)?

This can be extended in the obvious way to CTL-QUERY, CTL-SAT, CTL-VALID. We assume that the reader is familiar with P, NP, NP-hard, NP-complete, co-NP, â¦

PSPACE
TM only needs polynomially large tape.
PSPACE-hard
All problems \(P\) such that every problem from PSPACE can be reduced to \(P\).
PSPACE-complete
All problems that are in PSPACE and PSPACE-hard.

Theorem 7

The LTL model-checking and sat problem are co-NP-hard.

Reducing HAM-CYCLE to LTL-UNSAT

Because HAM-CYCLE is in NP we know that LTL-SAT is in co-NP.

\[\varphi:= \neg \left( \bigwedge_{v \in V} \diamond v \land \square(v \rightarrow \bigcirc\square\neg v) \right)\]

Theorem 8

The LTL model-checking problem is PSPACE-complete

Proving PSPACE-hardness of LTL-QUERY

Simulation and Bisimulation

Definition 21 (Bisimulation Relation) Let \(TS, TS'\) be two transition systems. A relation \(\mathfrak{R} \subseteq (S \cup S')^2\) is a bisimulation for \((TS, TS')\) if:

  • \(\mathfrak{R}\) is symetric
  • \(\mathfrak{R}\) is compatible with the labeling: \((s, s') \in \mathfrak{R} \Rightarrow L(s) = L'(s')\)
  • The initial states are similar in the sense that:
    • for all \(s \in S_0\) there exists \(s' \in S_0'\) such that \((s, s') \in \mathfrak{R}\)
    • for all \(s' \in S_0'\) there exists \(s \in S_0\) such that \((s, s') \in \mathfrak{R}\)
  • Successor states are similar3 in the sense that for all \((s, s') \in \mathfrak{R}\):
    • for all \(p \in Post(s)\) there exists \(p' \in Post(s')\) such that \((p, p') \in \mathfrak{R}\)
    • for all \(p' \in Post(s')\) there exists \(p \in Post(s')\) such that \((p, p') \in \mathfrak{R}\)

Definition 22 (AP Deterministic) A transition system \(TS\) is AP-deterministic if

  • \(|S_0| \leq 1\)
  • for all \(A \in 2^\texttt{AP}\) we have that \(|Post(s) \cap \{ s' \in S | L(s') = A \}| \leq 1\)

Theorem 9 (Bisimilarity vs Trace Equivalence)

For transition systems \(TS_1, TS_2\)

\[TS_1 \sim TS_2 \Rightarrow TS_1 \equiv_{trace} TS_2\]

For AP-deterministic transition systems \(TS_1, TS_2\)

\[TS_1 \sim TS_2 \Leftrightarrow TS_1 \equiv_{trace} TS_2\]

Corollary 2 For transition system TS and states \(s, s'\) it is equivalent:

  • \(s \sim s'\)
  • \(s \equiv_{CTL} s'\)
  • \(s \equiv_{CTL*} s'\)

Fairness

Fairness limits the set of traces we consider when doing model checking.

We want to remove traces that we consider unrealistic.

Which fairness notion?:

  • strong fairness good for contentions
  • weak fairness good for unfair scheduling

Fairness is concerned with a fair resolution of non-determinism.

Definition 23 (LTL Fairness Constraints) An LTL fairness constraint is of the form:

\[fair = ufair \land sfair \land wfair\]

where

  1. unconditional fairness constraint: \(ufair = \square\diamond\psi\)
  2. strong fairness constraint: \(sfair = \square\diamond\varphi\rightarrow \square\diamond\psi\)
  3. weak fairness constraint: \(wfair = \diamond\square\varphi\rightarrow \square\diamond\varphi\)

Corollary 3 (Fairness Suffix Property) For any fair path \(\pi\) it holds

  1. all suffixes of \(\pi\) are fair
  2. for any finite path fragment \(\sigma\) the extension \(\sigma.\pi\) is fair

Definition 24 (Realisable Fairness) A fairness assumption \(fair\) is realisable for \(TS\) iff. for all reachable states \(s\):

\[FairPaths_{fair}(s) = \{\pi \in Paths(s) \mid \pi \models fair \} \neq \emptyset\]

this is equivalent to

Every initial finite path fragment can be completed to a fair run.

Corollary 4 (Safety Properties are preserved under realisable fairness)

\[TS \models E_{safe} \text{ iff. } TS \models_{fair} E_{safe}\]

  • LTL formula \(\varphi\)
  • an LTL fairness assumption \(fair\)

Question: does \(TS \models_{fair} \varphi\)

Can be reduced to normal model checking by considering \((fair \rightarrow \varphi)\)

  • transition system \(TS\)
  • CTL formula \(\varphi\)
  • an CTL fairness assumption \(fair\)

Question: does \(TS \models_{fair} \varphi\)

include fairness checking by limiting \(\forall, \exists\) quantifiers to fair paths.

Definition 25 For \(TS = (S, \texttt{Act}, \rightarrow, I, \texttt{AP}, L)\) and its coarsest bisimulation \(\sim_{TS} \subseteq S \times S\). We define the quotient transition system

\[TS / \sim_{TS} = (S / \sim_{TS}, \{\tau\}, \rightarrow', I', \texttt{AP}, L')\]

where

  • \(S / \sim_{TS} = \{ [s]_\sim | s \in S \}\)
  • \(I' = \{ [s]_\sim | s \in I \}\)
  • \(L'([s]_\sim) = L(s)\)
  • \(s \rightarrow' s' \Leftrightarrow [s]_\sim \rightarrow [s']_\sim\)

Theorem 10

Every transition system is bisimilar to its bisimulation quotient.

Simulation Preorder

Definition 26 (Abstraction Function)

\(f : S \rightarrow \hat{S}\) is an abstraction function if \(f(s) = f(s') \Rightarrow L(s) = L(s')\)

Definition 27 (Abstraction Transition System) For \(TS = (S, \textcolor{gray}{\texttt{Act}}, \rightarrow, I, \textcolor{gray}{\texttt{AP}}, L)\) and abstraction function \(f : S \rightarrow \hat{S}\) we define the abstraction of \(TS\):

\[TS_f = (\hat{S}, \textcolor{gray}{\texttt{Act}}, \rightarrow_f, I_f, \textcolor{gray}{AP}, L)\]

  • \(f(s) \rightarrow_f f(s') \Leftrightarrow s \rightarrow s'\)
  • \(I_f = f(I)\)
  • \(L_f(f(s)) = L(s)\) (well defined because \(f\) is an abstraction)

Lemma 2

The relation \(\mathfrak{R} = \{ (s, f(s)) | s \in S \}\) is a simulation for \((TS, TS_f)\).

Definition 28 (Simulation Equivalence)

\[TS_1 \approxeq TS_2 \quad \text{ iff. } \quad TS_1 \leq TS_2 \text{ and } TS_2 \leq TS_1\]

Definition 29 (Universal fragment of \(CTL^*\)) State formulas:

\[\Phi ::= \texttt{true}| \texttt{false}| a | \neg a | \Phi \land \Phi | \Phi \lor \Phi | \forall \varphi\]

Path formulas:

\[\varphi::= \Phi | \bigcirc\varphi| \varphi\land \varphi| \varphi\lor \varphi| \varphi\textbf{U}\varphi| \varphi\textbf{R}\varphi\]

Lemma 3

For every LTL formula there exists an equivalent \(\forall CTL^*\) formula

Theorem 11 (Simulation equivalence and \(CTL\)) Let \(TS\) be a finitely branching and \(s, s'\) states in \(TS\). Then it is equivalent:

  • \(\Leftrightarrow\) \(s \leq s'\)
  • \(\Leftrightarrow\) for any \(\Phi \in \forall CTL^*\): \((s \models \Phi) \Leftarrow (s' \models \Phi)\)
  • \(\Leftrightarrow\) for any \(\Phi \in \forall CTL\): \((s \models \Phi) \Leftarrow (s' \models \Phi)\)
  • \(\Leftrightarrow\) for any \(\Phi \in \forall CTL_{\setminus \textbf{U}, \textbf{R}}\): \((s \models \Phi) \Leftarrow (s' \models \Phi)\)

Stuttering

Definition 30 (Stutter step)

A transition \(s \rightarrow s'\) is a stutter step if \(L(s) = L(s')\)

Definition 31 (Stutter Path Equivalence)

Paths \(\pi_1\) and \(\pi_2\) are stutter equivalent if \(trace(\pi_1)\) and \(trace(\pi_2)\) are both of the form \(A_0^+A_1^+A_2^+...\)

Definition 32 (Stutter Trace Equivalence) Transitionsystems \(TS_1, TS_2\) are stutter trace equivalent if

\[Traces(TS_1) /_{\equiv_\text{sttrace}} \ = \ Traces(TS_2) /_{\equiv_\text{sttrace}}\]

Definition 33 (Stutter Bisimilarity)

Stutter Path
Trace that only stutters. We say it diverges.
Divergent state
A state from which there exists a stutter path.
Stutter Bisimilarity vs Stutter Trace Equivalence

Stutter bisimilarity DOES NOT imply stutter trace equivalence. This is because stutter bisimilarity does not impose constraints on stutter paths.

Definition 34 (Divergent-Sensitive Stutter Bisimilarity)

Bisimilarity where divergent states are only paired with divergent states.

Divergent-Sensitive Stutter Bisimilarity vs Stutter Trace Equivalence

Divergent-sensitive stutter trace bisimilarity implies stutter trace equivalence.

Theorem 12 (Divergent-Sensitive Stutter Bisimilarity vs CTL) For a finitely branching \(TS\) and states \(s, s'\) it is equivalent:

  • \(\Leftrightarrow\) \(s \approx^{div}_{TS} s'\)
  • \(\Leftrightarrow\) \(s \equiv_{CTL_{\setminus \bigcirc}} s'\)
  • \(\Leftrightarrow\) \(s \equiv_{CTL_{\setminus \bigcirc}^*} s'\)

Stutter Cycle
Cycle that only consists of stutter steps. All states on a stutter cycle are divergent-sensitive stutter bisimilar

Performance Improvements

  • Find SCCs that only contain stutter steps
  • Collapse every Stutter SCC into a single state
Exit/Bottom state
state in a block whose successors are all outside the block.

No stutter cycles => each block has an exit state

For finite TS without stutter cycles:

\[B \setminus Pre_\Pi^*(B, C) \neq \emptyset \Leftrightarrow Bottom(B) \setminus Pre(C) \neq \emptyset\]

Time Complexity: \(O(\# \text{states} \cdot \# \text{transitions})\)

  • Definition 35 (Divergence Expansion)
  • Add new state \(s_{div}\) with \(L(s_{div}) = div\)
  • Add selfloop \(s_{div} \rightarrow^\tau s_{div}\)
  • Add edge from every divergent state on a stutter cycle to \(s_{div}\)

On this expanded TS divergent-sensitive stutter bisimilarity and normal stutter bisimilarity coincide.

Destillation: * replace \(s \rightarrow s_{div}\) with \([s] \rightarrow [s]\) * delete \(s_{div}\)

Partial Order Reduction

Idea
Sometimes the order of actions is not important. We can reduce the statespace by choosing one ârepresentativeâ permutation of independent actions.

Definition 36 (Action Deterministic) \(TS\) is action deterministic iff for all states \(s\):

\[s \xrightarrow{\alpha} u \land s \xrightarrow{\alpha} v \Rightarrow u=v\]

How to make a TS action deterministic

If for some state \(s\) there exists two outgoing edges with the same action \(\alpha\) we introduce a new action \(\alpha'\) and label one of the edges with it.

Definition 37 (Action Independence) Let \(TS\) be an action-deterministic transition system. Then \(\alpha, \beta \in \texttt{Act}\) are called independent if for all states with \(\alpha, \beta \in \texttt{Act}(s)\):

\[\beta \in \texttt{Act}(\alpha(s)) \land \alpha \in \texttt{Act}(\beta(s)) \land \beta(\alpha(s)) = \alpha(\beta(s))\]

We say \(\alpha\) is independent of \(B \subseteq \texttt{Act}\setminus \{\alpha\}\) iff alpha is independent of every action in \(B\).

Stutter Action
An action where each transition is a stutter step.

Definition 38 (Ample Sets) For each state \(s\) we select a subset of outgoing edges \(ample(s) \subseteq \texttt{Act}(s)\) that satisfies the following conditions:

  1. Non-emptiness condition Select at least one action in every state. \(\forall s. ample(s) \neq \emptyset\)
  2. Dependency condition in the original TS: an action depending on \(ample(s)\) can only occur after some action in \(ample(s)\) has occurred.
  3. Stutter condition If an enabled action is not selected, then all selected actions are stutter actions. \(\forall s. (ample(s) \neq Act(s) \rightarrow ample(s) \subseteq Act_{stutter})\)
  4. Cycle condition Any action in \(\texttt{Act}(s_i)\) (in TS) with \(s_i\) on a cycle in \(TS_{red}\) must be selected in some \(s_i\) on that cycle.

Corollary 5 For every \(s \in Reach(TS)\) and \(\alpha \in ample(s)\) we can conclude from 1. that:

  • $is independent of \(Act(s) \setminus ample(s)\).
  • If there is a path \(s = s_0 \rightarrow^{\beta_1} ... \rightarrow^{\beta_n} s_n\) in TS and \(\beta_1,...,\beta_n \notin ample(s)\) then: \(\alpha\) is independent of \(\{\beta_1,...,\beta_n\}\) and thereby \(\forall_{0 \leq i \leq n} \alpha \in Act(s_i)\)

Definition 39 (Ample Set Reduction) For \(TS\) and ample sets \(ample: S \rightarrow 2^\texttt{Act}\) we define the reduced transition system

\[TS_{red} := (S', \texttt{Act}, \Rightarrow, I, \texttt{AP}, L_{|S'})\]

where:

  • \(s \Rightarrow^\alpha s'\) iff. \(s \rightarrow^\alpha s' \land \alpha \in ample(s)\)
  • \(S'\) are all states that are reachable via \(\Rightarrow\)
  • \(L_{|S'} : S \rightarrow \mathfrak{P}(\texttt{AP}), s \mapsto L(s)\) is the reduction of \(L\) to \(S'\).

Symbolic Model Checking

Evaluation
Function that assigns a value to every variable \(\nu : Var \rightarrow \{0, 1\}\)
Switching Function
A function that assigns a boolean value to an evaluation \(f : 2^{Var} \rightarrow \{0, 1\}\). Can be used to encode sets

Representing Switching Functions

Binary Decision Tree (BDT)
Full binary tree of depth \(\#\text{variables}\) The path to a leaf encodes an evaluation.
Ordered Binary Decision Diagram (OBDD)
Acyclic Graph. Isomorphic subgraphs are collapsed into one node.

\(f_v = \underbrace{(z \land (f_{succ_1(v)})) \lor (\neg z \land (f_{succ_0(v)}))}_\text{Shannon expansion}\)

Definition 40 (Consistent Cofactor) Let \(v_1 <_\rho ... <_\rho v_n\) be some variabel order and \(f\) a switching function on \(Var = \{v_1,...,v_n\}\). Then \(g\) is a consistent cofactor iff

\[\exists i.\exists c_1,...,c_i. (g = f|_{[v_1=c_1,...,v_i = c_i]})\]

In other words

\[g : 2^{n-i} \rightarrow \{0, 1\} \ , \ (x_{i+1}, ... x_{n}) \mapsto f(\textcolor{gray}{c_1,...,c_i},x_{i+1}, ..., x_n)\]

Reduced OBDD
OBDD without isomorphic subtrees.

Theorem 13 (Universality and Canonicity) For finite \(Var\), fixed ordering and switching function.

  1. There exists a ROBDD
  2. Each pair of switching functions is isomorphic
Essential Variable
A variable \(x\) is essential iff \(f|_{[x=1]} \neq f|_{[x=0]}\).
Symmtric function
Generalisation of kommutativity to functions with \(\geq 2\) arguments. Means that function result is independent of permutation of inputs. \(f(x) = f(\sigma(x))\) for every permutation \(\sigma\).

Lemma 4 (Size of ROBDD for Symmetric Functions)

Let \(f\) be a symmetric function with \(m\) essential variables. Then for each variable ordering the ROBDD has size \(O(m^2)\)

Finding best permutation of variables is very hard.

Variable Sifting
Choose some x_i. For all j try order: \(x_1,...x_{j-1}, x_i, x_{j},...,x_n\)
Interleaved Variable Order
Encode binary relation \((x, y)\) with n bits as \(x_1,y_1,x_2,y_2,...x_n, y_n\). In practice good to encode transition relations.
Shared OBDD
ROBDD with multiple root nodes. Can be used to encode multiple switching functions.

Implementation of SOBDDs

  1. unique table
  • entries: \(\langle var(v), succ_1(v), succ_0(v) \rangle\)
  • main operation: find_or_add(z, v1, v2)
  • keeps track of already created nodes
  • implemented using hash-tables

Definition 41 (ITE normal form) We introduce the if-then-else operator \(ITE(g, f_1, f_2) := (g \land f_1) \lor (\neg g \land f_0)\)

We can âpushâ substitutions inside:

\[(ITE(g, f_1, f_2)) |_{[v := b]} = ITE(g|_{[v := b]}, f_1|_{[v := b]}, f_2|_{[v := b]})\]

Convert ITE to SOBDD:

\[\frac{f := ITE (g, f_1, f_2)}{ ITE (v^\bot, f|_{[v^\bot := 1]}, f|_{[v^\bot := 0]}) }\]

where \(v^\bot\) is the least variabel according to our variable ordering.

SAT-based Bounded Model Checking

Checks for bugs of bounded length.

Only used for LTL because CTL-counterexamples are harder to reason about.

Idea
For a given \(k\): unroll the TS to paths of length \(k\) and check for property. Unroll formulas as well.

Definition 42 An infinite path \(\rho\) is a \((k, l)\)-lasso iff:

\[\forall i \geq 0. \quad \rho(l+i) = \rho(k+1 + i)\]

i.e.Â the path is of the form

\[\underbrace{s_0 s_1 s_2 ... s_{l-1}}_\text{stem} \underbrace{(s_l ... s_k)^\omega}_\text{loop}\]
